{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"89d78a53-2327-4117-85f3-3a9198ea9e2b","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what you need to bring workloads (like `maui`) in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — reinstalls the **same versions** already recorded. It fixes corrupted or incomplete installations but won't pull newer workload versions that a new SDK may require.\n\n**TL;DR:** SDK changed → versions need to catch up → `dotnet workload update`. If the build still fails after that, also try `dotnet workload restore` from your project directory to ensure all project-required workloads are installed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b0432003-5244-46d8-ac94-b4ec8936a0f5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing a .NET MAUI build issue after an SDK update. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":247,"requestId":"9BC4:11AB75:61F4C96:6D1DAD4:69EC0E1D"},"id":"e3196de6-111b-4285-bb30-67541d44c655","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:43:17.354Z","parentId":"c1883a7c-7223-467a-bda6-0acde5f658a6"}
